---
import VizPlaceholder from '../../VizPlaceholder.astro';
---

<section
  id="knowledge"
  class="border-y border-neutral-900 bg-neutral-900/40 px-6 py-20 md:py-28"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <h2
        class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
      >
        The knowledge walks out the door
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
        Think about how this plays out at a company, because the session problem
        is really a knowledge problem. As your responsibility rises, you stop
        reading every implementation. As a system architect you care that the
        data flows through the application the right way; you do not sit at the
        keyboard of every developer shipping a feature. The developer holds those
        details. And when that developer changes jobs, the knowledge leaves with
        them, because it was almost never written down.
      </p>
    </div>

    <figure class="mx-auto mt-14 max-w-4xl border-y border-neutral-800 py-10 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-medium leading-snug text-neutral-100 sm:text-3xl">
        Agents are developers who <span class="text-accent"
          >leave after every single task</span
        >.
      </p>
    </figure>

    <div class="mt-14 grid items-center gap-12 lg:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
        <p>
          The reasoning that went into an implementation is right there while the
          session runs, and then the session ends and the agent forgets. Session
          logs exist, but they are
          <mark>local to one machine, invisible to the org</mark>. The workaround
          people reach for is ADRs, architectural decision records, but it is a
          workaround: where do you store them, and how do you share them across
          an organization? The multiplayer nature of agentic work, many people
          and many agents drawing on the same accumulated understanding, is the
          part nobody has solved with a document.
        </p>
        <p class="font-medium text-neutral-100">
          A meta-harness turns sessions into shared organizational memory. The
          reasoning stops walking out the door, because it never lived behind one
          door to begin with.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <VizPlaceholder
          label="SessionMemoryBeforeAfter island"
          ratio="aspect-[16/10]"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
